description: From Irish boicín, the diminutive of boc. Equivalent to buck +‎ -een.

entries.meaning: (Ireland, historical) a poor young man of the lower Anglo-Irish gentry who aspires to the habits and dress of the wealthy. [from 18th c.]
examples: Probably no other country could produce such a degraded type as the squireen or buckeen, the drunken, gambling, profligate descendant of the Cromwellian or Williamite settler.
